n+ Group''' is a Russian energy and metals company. It has a controlling stake in [[Rusal]] (the second largest producer of aluminium in the world) and is the world's largest independant [[hydropower]] generator in the world.\n\nIt is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]].\n\n==History==\n'''2002:''' En+ Group was established with predominant focus on the production of aluminium and [[Aluminium oxide|alumina]].\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2003:''' [[Rusal|RUSAL Holding Limited]] was established following the corporate [[restructuring]] and [[consolidation (business)|consolidation]] of aluminium and alumina assets. These assets would later form the group of companies that now comprise UC RUSAL. The consolidation of RUSAL Holding Limited was completed in 2004, 100% of its shares were transferred to En+ Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enplus.ru/upload/iblock/adf/adfcbd602378f13473edb877ccad8b53.pdf|title=En+ Group plc}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2003:''' The Group acquired 64.0% of shares in [[Krasnoyarsk Dam|Krasnoyarsk HPP]], currently the tenth largest [[Hydro power plant|HPP]] globally in terms of installed capacity. Between 2003 and 2007, the Group acquired a further 4.3% interest in Krasnoyarsk HPP. In 2016, the Group increased its shareholding to 100%.\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2001 \u2013 2007:''' The Group acquired 50.2% of the shares of [[Irkutskenergo]], a power company that owns the [[Irkutsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Irkutsk]], [[Bratsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Bratsk]] and [[Ust-Ilimsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Ust-Ilimsk]] HPPs and several [[Cogeneration|CHPs]] in the [[Irkutsk Oblast|Irkutsk region]] of Russia, with an aggregate generation capacity of 12.8 GW. In 2016 the Group increased its shareholding to 90.8%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.irkutskenergo.ru/news/3675.html|title=Irkutskenergo. En+ Group completes the acquisition of a 40.29% shareholding in Irkutskenergo from Inter RAO|website=en.irkutskenergo.ru|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2007:''' Following the acquisitions of SUAL Group by En+ Group, which at the time was one of the ten largest aluminium producers globally, and select aluminium and alumina businesses from [[Glencore]], the current RUSAL was formed under UC RUSAL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2006/08/30/russian-merger-to-create-world-s-top-aluminium-producer|title=Russian merger to create world's top aluminium producer|date=30 August 2006|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2008:''' UC RUSAL completed the acquisition of a 25% + 1 shares stake in [[Nornickel|Norilsk Nickel]], the world's second largest producer of [[Nickel]] and one of the world's leading producers of [[platinum]] and [[copper]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/rusal-norilsk-idUKL2475501720080424|title=UPDATE 5-UC RUSAL buys 25 pct of Russian miner Norilsk|date=24 April 2008|work=Reuters|access-date=23 January 2019|language=en}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2010''': UC UC RUSAL held its initial public offering of shares and depositary receipts in [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8bc796a4-0699-11df-b952-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref> The company later listed shares and depositary receipts on the [[Moscow Exchange]].\n\n'''2011''': En+ established En+ logistics, to provide [[logistics]] services predominantly to its Energy Segment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalinfo.ru/en/news/52302|title=En + Group has opened permanent train traffic across the bridge over the river Abakan in Hakassia - Russian Metallurgy news - Metal Supply and Sales Magazine|website=www.metalinfo.ru|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2014:''' Boguchansk HPP initiated operations (as part of the BEMO 50/50 joint venture between UC RUSAL and [[RusHydro]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eng.rushydro.ru/industry/invest/key_projects/boguchanskaya_hpp/|title=Boguchanskaya HPP|website=www.eng.rushydro.ru|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2016:''' The first half of the first stage of the Boguchansk aluminium smelter (as part of the BEMO 50/50 joint venture between UC RUSAL and RusHydro) began operations with a production capacity of 149 thousand tonnes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/united-co-rusal-results-idUSL4N16H3IH|title=UPDATE 1-Russia's Rusal to start Boguchansk aluminium smelter in H1|date=9 March 2016|work=Reuters|access-date=23 January 2019|language=en}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n'''2017''': En+ successfully lists on the [[London Stock Exchange]], raising $1.5 billion from international investors, valuing the company at $8 billion. The [[Initial public offering|IPO]] was largest Russian IPO globally since 2012 and the first IPO by a Russian company in London since 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lseg.com/resources/media-centre/press-releases/russia%E2%80%99s-en-group-lists-london-stock-exchange|title=Russia\u2019s En+ Group lists on London Stock Exchange|website=London Stock Exchange Group|language=en|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\n=== US sanctions on En+ Group ===\nOn 6 April 2018 En+ Group was added to the [[Office of Foreign Assets Control|SDN-list]] of the [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm0338|title=Treasury Designates Russian Oligarchs, Officials, and Entities in Response to Worldwide Malign Activity {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury|website=home.treasury.gov|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref> On 27 April 2018 the chairman of the board of directors of the Group [[Greg Barker, Baron Barker of Battle|Lord Gregory Barker]] crafted a plan aimed at the de-listing of the company from the sanctions\u2019 list (\u201cThe Barker plan\u201d). The plan envisaged the reduction of [[Oleg Deripaska|Deripaska]]\u2019s shareholding to below 50% and the creation of an independent board of directors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=0a0d8a20-1eee-11e9-bd9f-41445c9badd0&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOC0wNy0yNS9lbi1yZWFkeS10by1pbXBsZW1lbnQtc2FuY3Rpb25zLXJlbGllZi1wbGFuLWFzLWRlYWRsaW5lLWxvb21z|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2018 the US Treasury extended the general licences, allowing for certain activities to sanctioned entities till 6 June 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20180501.aspx|title=\u00e2\u20ac\u2039\u00e2\u20ac\u2039Issuance of Ukraine-/Russia-related General Licenses; Publication of New FAQs and Updated FAQs|website=www.treasury.gov|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref> (there were multiple extensions afterwards, the last on till 28 January 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20190116.aspx|title=Temporary Extension of Ukraine-related General Licenses|website=www.treasury.gov|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July 2018 US Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] said in an interview that the objective was not to put the company out of business, but to limit Oleg Deripaska.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-g20-argentina-mnuchin-rusal-exclusive-idUSKBN1KA2VS|title=Exclusive: U.S. open to lifting sanctions off aluminum giant Rusal...|date=21 July 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=23 January 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018 the US Treasury notified the [[United States Congress|Congress]] about its intention to lift sanctions against En+ Group following the corporate restructuring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm576|title=OFAC Notifies Congress of Intent to Delist En+, Rusal, and EuroSibEnergo {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury|website=home.treasury.gov|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Governance ==\nIn accordance with the agreement with [[Office of Foreign Assets Control|OFAC]] the board of directors of En+ Group will consist of twelve directors with a majority of independent directors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-russia-sanctions-deripaska-rusal-idUSKCN1OK081|title=Biting the bullet, not the dust: Deripaska gives up his aluminum...|date=21 December 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=23 January 2019|language=en}}</ref> The Chairman of the Board of Directors is the Rt Hon Lord Barker of Battle PC.\n\nLord Barker was appointed as the Chairman of the Board of Directors in October 2017. In August 2015, Gregory Barker was made a life Peer and, since October 2015, has been a member of the [[House of Lords]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]. Lord Barker served as member of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|British House of Commons]] from 2001 to 2015. From 2010 to 2014, Lord Barker served as UK Minister of State for Energy & Climate Change, becoming the longest serving British energy minister for a generation.\n\nThe Chief executive officer of the Group is Vladimir Kiryukhin and the Chief operating officer is Vyacheslav Solomin.\n\n== Shareholding structure ==\nFollowing the implementation of the Barker plan the shareholding of Oleg Deripaska will be cut to 44.95% and he will not be able to vote more than 35% of En+ Group shares.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/05a0576e-1af8-11e9-9e64-d150b3105d21|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Group activities ==\nEn+ Group's operations combine 19.6 GW of installed electricity capacity, 75% of which are hydro power stations and aluminium production 3.9 mnt, which makes En+ Group the largest aluminium producer outside of China and the largest independent hydro power generating company globally.\n\n=== Metals ===\n[[Rusal]], in which En+ Group holds a 48.1% stake, thereby providing the Group with strategic control, is a vertically-integrated aluminium producer. UC RUSAL is a clear low-cost leader in the production of aluminium, and accounted for approximately 6.2% of global aluminium output based on 2017 results.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rusal.ru/upload/iblock/327/LTN20180427141%20ar.pdf|title=RUSAL Annual report 2017}}</ref>\n\nEn+ Group's Metals segment operates 10 [[aluminium smelter]]s and 7 alumina refineries, with its core smelting operations located in [[Siberia]]. In addition, UC RUSAL holds a strategic investment in [[Nornickel|Norilsk Nickel]] and a 50% interest in the BEMO Project (a joint venture between UC RUSAL and RusHydro comprising [[Boguchany Dam|Boguchansk HPP]] and [[Boguchany Aluminium Smelter|Boguchansk aluminium smelter]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enplus.ru/upload/iblock/c85/c8575d75191b237d0d09fd80c6843c6a.pdf|title=En+ Annual report 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 En+ Group's Metals segment produced 3,707 thousand tonnes of aluminium, 7,773 thousand tonnes of alumina and 11,645 thousand tonnes of [[bauxite]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enplus.ru/upload/iblock/f39/f39a6115f1afe4f4305168831115bec9.pdf|title=En+ 2017 Operational results}}</ref>\n\n==== Key assets of the En+ Group Metals segment ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+style=\"text-align: left\"|Aluminium smelters\n!Country\n!Name\n!Location\n!Start of operations\n!'''Annual production capacity, ktpa'''\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Krasnoyarsk Aluminium Smelter\n|[[Krasnoyarsk]]\n|1964\n|1019\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Bratsk Aluminium Smelter\n|[[Bratsk]]\n|1966\n|1008\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Boguchansk Aluminium Smelter\u00a0 \u00a0\n|Taezhny town\u00a0 \u00a0\n|2016\n|588\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Irkutsk Aluminium Smelter\u00a0 \u00a0\n|[[Shelekhov]]\u00a0 \u00a0\n|1962\n|529\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Sayanogorsk Aluminium Smelter\u00a0 \u00a0\n|[[Sayanogorsk]]\n|1985\n|524\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Novokuznetsk Aluminium Smelter\u00a0 \u00a0\n|[[Novokuznetsk]]\n|