|2004\n|1,7\n|}\n\n=== Energy ===\nEn+ Group operates generating assets with 19.6 GW of installed electricity capacity. As of 31 December 2016, hydro power plants accounted for 76.6% (15.1 GW) of the Group's installed electricity capacity, which makes the Company the largest privately held hydro power generation company globally. As at 31 December 2016, the Group held an 8% share of the total installed electricity capacity in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enplus.ru/upload/iblock/757/7573403591c1c609c50bd503983a940e.pdf|title=EN+ GROUP PLC ANNOUNCES INTENTION TO FLOAT ON THE LONDON STOCK EXCHANGE AND MOSCOW EXCHANGE}}</ref>\n\nThe Group's power assets are predominantly located in Siberia, where it has a 37.6% share of total installed electricity capacity in the region. The hydro power operations benefit from the abundant water resources of the [[Angara River|Angara]] and [[Yenisei River|Yenisei]] river cascades. These plants provide sustainable, [[Low-carbon power|low carbon]] and low-cost power for Russian industrial facilities, including Metals segment's core aluminium smelters. The Group believes that it benefits from lower operating costs compared to other hydro power generation companies in part due to the geographic location, scale and efficient management of the power generating assets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/638e1dc6-1bb2-11e7-bcac-6d03d067f81f|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nEn+ Group's Energy segment is a member of the Global Sustainable Electricity Partnership, a non-profit organisation whose members are the world's leading electricity companies, supplying energy to over 1.2 billion customers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalelectricity.org/members/eurosibenergo-ese/|title=EuroSibEnergo (ESE)|website=GSEP|language=en-US|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, En+ Group produced 68.4TWh of electricity and 26.7mn Gcal of heat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enplus.ru/upload/iblock/f39/f39a6115f1afe4f4305168831115bec9.pdf|title=En+ 2017 Operational results}}</ref>\n\n==== Key assets of the En+ Group Energy segment ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+style=\"text-align: left\"|Hydropower plants\n!Country\n!Name\n!Location\n!Start of operations\n!'''Installed capacity, MW'''\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|[[Krasnoyarsk Dam|Krasnoyarsk HPP]]\n|[[Divnogorsk]]\n|1972 \u2014\n|6000\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|[[Bratsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Bratsk HPP]]\n|[[Bratsk]]\n|1966 \u2014\n|4500\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|[[Ust-Ilimsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Ust-Ilimsk HPP]]\u00a0 \u00a0\n|[[Ust-Ilimsk]]\u00a0 \u00a0\n|1980 \u2014\n|3840\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|[[Irkutsk Hydroelectric Power Station|Irkutsk HPP]]\n|[[Irkutsk]]\n|1956 \u2014\n|662\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+style=\"text-align: left\"|Combined heat plants\n!Country\n!Name\n!Location\n!Start of operations\n!'''Installed capacity, MW'''\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|CHP-10\n|Angarsk\n|1959\n|1100\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|CHP-9\n|Angarsk\n|1963\n|540\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Novo-Irkutsk CHP\n|Irkutsk\n|1975\n|708\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Ust-Ilimsk CHP\u00a0 \u00a0\n|Ust-Ilimsk\u00a0 \u00a0\n|1978\n|515\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|CHP-11\n|Usolye-Sibirskoye\n|1959\n|350\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|CHP-6\n|Bratsk\n|1965\n|270\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Novo-Ziminskaya CHP\u00a0 \u00a0\n|Sayansk\n|1980\n|260\n|-\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Avtozavodskaya CHP\u00a0 \u00a0\n|Nizhny Novgorod\u00a0 \u00a0\n|1931\n|580\n|}\n== Renewables ==\n\nIn 2015 En+ Group commenced the operations of the Abakan solar power plant. Its installed capacity is 5.2 MW, which makes it the largest solar power plant of Eastern Siberia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sayanring.com/news/abakan-launched-the-largest-in-siberia-solar-power-plant.htm|title=Abakan launched the largest in Siberia solar power plant. \u00b7 News \u00b7 Tour Operator \u00abSayan Ring\u00bb - welcome to Siberia|website=www.sayanring.com|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Key figures ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+style=\"text-align: left\"|'''Financial data in USD billions'''\n![[Year]]\n!9M2018\n!9M2017\n!FY2017\n!FY2016\n|-\n|[[Revenue]]\n|9,434\n|8,716\n|12,094\n|9,776\n|-\n|[[Adj. EBITDA]]\n|2,618\n|2,316\n|3,223\n|2,311\n|-\n|[[Net profit]]\n|1,623\n|898\n|1,403\n|1,361\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+style=\"text-align: left\"|'''Operational highlights'''\n!\n!Measurement unit\n!9M2018\n!9M2017\n!FY2017\n!FY2016\n|-\n|Aluminium production\n|Tonnes, 000\n|2,810\n|2,762\n|3,707\n|3,685\n|-\n|Primary aluminium and alloy sales\n|Tonnes, 000\n|2,794\n|2,955\n|3,955\n|3,818\n|-\n|Alumina production\n|Tonnes, 000\n|5,816\n|5,782\n|7,773\n|7,527\n|-\n|Bauxite production\n|Tonnes, 000\n|10,128\n|8,701\n|11,645\n|12,187\n|-\n|Total electricity generation\n|TWh\n|53,2\n|50,4\n|68,4\n|69,5\n|-\n|Total heat generation\n|Gcal, 000\n|18,4\n|17,5\n|26,7\n|27,4\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Russia|Energy|Companies}}\n* {{official|http://www.enplus.ru }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721132537/http://www.deripaska.com/ Oleg Deripaska / Oleg deripaska website]\n\n[[Category:Mining companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Electric power companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Basic Element (company)]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Moscow Exchange]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: independant \u2192 independent", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/En%2B_Group"}
